  "prompt": "What is the electron configuration of electron?",
  "response": "The electron doesn't have a configuration itself; rather, the term \"electron configuration\" refers to the arrangement of electrons in an atom or ion. \n\nThe electron configuration describes the distribution of electrons among the various atomic orbitals. For instance, the electron configuration of a carbon atom (which has six electrons) is:\n\n1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u00b2\n\nHere, \n- \"1s\u00b2\" indicates that there are 2 electrons in the 1s orbital,\n- \"2s\u00b2\" indicates that there are 2 electrons in the 2s orbital, and\n- \"2p\u00b2\" indicates that there are 2 electrons in the 2p orbital.\n\nElectron configurations follow the Pauli exclusion principle, Hund's rule, and the Aufbau principle to determine the distribution of electrons in orbitals.",
